e Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gordon","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Gordon in Berwickshire, named with Welsh <i>gor</i> ‘spacious’ + <i>din</i> ‘fort’.","English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Gourdon in Saône-et-Loire, so called from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Gordus</i> + the locative suffix <i>-o</i>, <i>-ōnis</i>.","English (of Norman origin): alternatively, said to be a nickname from a diminutive of Old French <i>gourd</i> ‘heavy, dull, sluggish’ (compare 8 below)."],"variants":[{"name":"Gordin","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Eyal, Moisey, Yakov, Zalman, Erez, Faina, Haya, Mendel.  Russian Leonid, Aleksandr, Boris, Feiga, Genady.","Jewish (from Russia): variant of   Gordon   5.","French: variant of   Gourdin  . This surname is very rare in France."]},{"name":"Gordan","meanings":["German: variant of   Jordan  . The surname <i>Gordan</i> is very rare in Germany.","Irish (Wexford and Sligo): adopted as an Anglicized form of <b>Mag Mhuirneacháin</b> ‘son of <i>Muirneachán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>muirneach</i> ‘lovable’."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: The Scripture name, in Hebrew, Adham, signifying 'man;' literally earthy, red earth; Rudolph, however, says the name in Ethiopic means ' to be fair, beautiful.' Hence the nurse-name Addy, little Adam."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adam de Gordon 2nd Laird Gordon was born in 1135, in Gordon, Berwickshire, Scotland, his father, Sir Adam de Gordon 1st Laird Of Gordon, was 56 and his mother, Lady Alicia De Gordon, was 42. He married Mrs Adam De Gordon lll 2nd Laird Of Gordon in 1158, in Berwickshire, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1170, in Aberdeenshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 35."},"et":{"1135–1170":"11